New Castle County, in partnership with the State of Delaware and the Delaware Emergency Management Agency, is offering free COVID-19 testing at various sites around the county.
To see test site locations and dates, visit: https://www.nccde.org/2011/COVID-19-Resources

The tests are free, easy, open to the public, and painless. You do not have to register ahead, but if you do it will cut down on the time spent in line. The tests are self-administered oral swabs, provided by Curative. Participants swab the inside of their mouth, drop the swab into the tube, and drop off the package on their way out of the parking lot. The whole process takes less than 10 minutes, and even less if subjects are pre-registered. Participants do not need to have symptoms to receive the test. Test results are expected back to participants in 24-48 hours via email.

To pre-register for any of the testing sites in Delaware, guests can visit https://delaware.curativeinc.com/welcome

post_text:
We announced in early July that New Castle County Vo-Tech would be hosting a summer Teen Summit to provide students with a forum to share their experiences and to learn from each other.
We are excited to announce that the Teen Summit will take place on Tuesday, August 11, from 1-3 pm. The summit will be a virtual event where students will have a platform to learn about the issues and concerns regarding race, equity, and social justice.
During the Teen Summit, students will collaborate with each other and ask our speakers questions on what can be done to combat racism, inequalities, and social injustice.
Registration information for the event has been posted on Schoology and on your school’s website.
We hope you encourage your student to participate so all can come together to make positive changes in our schools.

The whole process takes less than 10 minutes, and even less if subjects are pre-registered. Participants do not need to have symptoms to receive the test. Test results are expected back to participants in 24-48 hours via email.

To pre-register for any of the testing sites in Delaware, guests can visit https://delaware.curativeinc.com/welcome

The tests are free, easy, open to the public, and painless. You do not have to register ahead, but if you do it will cut down on the time spent in line. The tests are self-administered oral swabs, provided by Curative. Participants swab the inside of their mouth, drop the swab into the tube, and drop off the package on their way out of the parking lot. The whole process takes less than 10 minutes, and even less if subjects are pre-registered. Participants do not need to have symptoms to receive the test. Test results are expected back to participants in 24-48 hours via email.

To pre-register for any of the testing sites in Delaware, guests can visit https://delaware.curativeinc.com/welcome

NCC Vo-Tech Families - Continue to check our Nutrition Services website at https://www.nccvtns.com/ as location and times for meal distribution are updated frequently.

Also, if you are using DART bus transportation to get to meal distribution sites,
DART is now limiting the number of passengers allowed on each bus at any given time, based on bus seating capacity. Passenger boardings will be through the rear door with no fare collection. Riders needing boarding assistance will be allowed to continue boarding through the front door.

In order to accommodate riders, DART will operate additional timing buses, as well as have additional operators on standby.

If you are feeling sick, please do not visit public facilities and avoid public transportation. For more information on the state’s response to the Coronavirus, visit de.gov/coronavirus.

post_text:
Social Distancing –
What Does That Really Mean?

As the number of Coronavirus cases continues to rise in our community, the Delaware Division of Public Health has provided additional recommendations for parents and families about social distancing:

• Avoid group gatherings for students, including sleepovers, play dates, parties, or teen groups.
• Those who do need childcare, try to limit the number of interactions and families involved as possible.
• If you are socializing with others, maintain 6 feet of distance between individuals outside of the immediate family.
• If outside for walks, hikes, bike rides, or other activities, it is important to still maintain 6 feet between people beyond immediate family and limit your group size.

All School Meal Sites Are Available to NCC Vo-Tech Students

School meals will be available for students who may need them during this time of the school closures.

Students who are 18 and under may receive meals at any distribution site listed on the Department of Education website ( https://www.doe.k12.de.us/covid19 ) or listed by any school district. Families may pick up meals for children 18 and under who live in their home. Children must be present for the pick-up. Sites are available throughout the State and the City of Wilmington. NCC Vo-Tech is not distributing meals at our schools, but our students will be served at any site that is offering meals. If you do not see a site located in your vicinity, please keep checking the Department of Education website, or site listings by other school districts, as they are being updated daily.

Also, information on site locations will be available by dialing 211.

post_text:
Need to Get Something You Forgot?

NCC Vo-Tech will open school buildings on Monday, March 16, between 9 and 11 a.m. Offices will not be open. This is in order for Parents/Guardians to retrieve any necessary medications from the School Nurse's office, to get a Chromebook or iPad and charger that was left if a student was absent last week and did not bring it home, etc. This will be the only time that schools will open next week. This is not a time for students to meet up at the school or for parents to ask questions or to drop off freshmen registrations. This is a courtesy to all for retrieval of an item your student must-have in the next two weeks.
𝗥𝗲𝗺𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗲𝗿: Students cannot retrieve a controlled medication prescription. It must be a parent or guardian.

post_text: Saturday, May 11 at Delcastle:
text: Saturday, May 11 at Delcastle:

post_text:
NCC Vo-Tech Celebrates Business Partnerships at Biennial Dinner 5/8/19!
Did you know that 776 seniors from Delcastle, Hodgson, Howard, and St. Georges were employed in more than 500 different Delaware companies and organizations this year as part of the district's co-op job placement program? That means 7 out of 10 vo-tech seniors are already gaining valuable work experience and making industry connections PRIOR to graduating from high school. We celebrated the companies who create these opportunities at a recognition dinner held May 8 at St. Georges. The evening featured speeches from four co-op students representing each school, Gov. John Carney, and Secretary of Labor Cerron Cade. Sen. Chris Coons provided a video greeting. NCCVTSD Nutrition Services staff from all four schools prepared and served dinner. The district recognized three companies that have hired co-op students for many years: the Delaware Community Reinvestment Advisory Council, MDavis, and RC Fabricators.

post_text: The Delcastle Drama Club proudly presents its second musical – Little Shop of Horrors – this week. There will be an afternoon performance on Thursday, April 11th, the doors open at 3 p.m. and the show starts at 3:15 p.m. Tickets for this performance are only $5 and are available at the door. The evening performances will be on Friday, April 12th and Saturday, April 13th. Doors open at 6:15 p.m. and the show starts at 7 p.m. Tickets for the evening shows are available online at a discount (https://delcastle.ludus.com/index.php) or at the door. See you at the show!
